<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-170  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 170.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 19 1990 v4 n7 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DLA moves to consolidate DOD contracting administration services.andO;(the Defense Logistics Agency to handle contract administrationfor the Army, Air Force and Navy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Defense Logistics Agency will handle all contractadministration for the Army, Navy and Air Force as specified inthe recent Defense Management Review (DMR).andP;  DLA will activate theDefense Contract Management Command (DCMC) on Feb 16, 1990, atCameron Station, VA; the plan will add 60,000 to 80,000 contractsto the 410,000 that DLA already manages, according to DLA DeputyAssistant Dir for Telecommunications and Information Systems BobbyL. Parsons.andP;  The contracts will be processed through the DLAMechanization of Contract Administrative Services system, whichmay require upgrading; the $1 billion DLA Logistics SystemsModernization Program will be shelved in favor of a lesscomplicated plan for new systems and solutions valued at about$200 million a year.andP;  The 17 DLA data processing installationswill be consolidated into about six facilities, according toParsons; other major DLA projects underway are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyGovernment ContractsMilitaryDefense ContractsAdministrative ServicesNational GovernmentOrganization StructureReorganizationManagement of EDPUnited States. Defense Logistics Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>